Date: Tue, 23 Sep 1997 17:36:35 -0400
From: Dorothy Preslar <dpreslar@fas.org>
Source: Media sources and a message from Dr. Mossbach Gerhard,
<ho1018@hof.baynet.de>

[Thanks to Dr. Mosbach Gerhard of the University of Zurich for calling this
incident to our attention on 23 September 97. The following is a news
report of the Lassa fever case in Germany. --es
MAINZ, Germany, Sept 22. German health authorities issued a health warning
for possible contacts of a Ghanaian national Monday after the man died of
Lassa fever.
The 37-year-old man died here Saturday, nine days after he was admitted to
hospital with symptoms similar to a common cold.
The viral disease is fatal in up to 20 percent of known cases.
Health officials were alerted in the Frankfurt and Duesseldorf regions to
find possible contacts and medical staff who spoke to the man, a spokesman
for the Robert Koch Institute in Berlin said.
The regional Rhineland-Palatinate health ministry said 50 people had already
undergone medical tests.
The Lassa virus, first identified in Niger in 1969, is transmitted between
humans by body fluids and airborne infection. [Evidence for human to human
transmission suggests that direct contact is more important than airborne
trasmission. --es
Last year 200 people were infected with the disease in Sierra Leone. More
than 60 people died.
--
