[The Lassa virus, first identified in Niger in 1969, is transmitted between
humans by body fluids and airborne infection. [Lassa virus was first
described in an outbreak in Nigeria NOT Niger, in a mission hospital on the
Jos Plateau. In another outbreak in Liberia, it was discovered the disease
was spread from rats _Mastomys natalensis_ to humans by urine. Lassa fever
was one of the earliest of deadly, hemorrhagic fevers to be dealt with in
terms of international travel and quarantine. An American was transported
home using an Apollo space capsule for isolation, and a German national was
stuck in Ibadan, Nigeria in 1974 until ostensibily safe transport and
quarantine measures were developed. Mod. pc
